283	
284	## Configuration
285	
286	All pipeline parameters live in TOML files.
287	
288	### `config/default.toml`
289	
290	| Section | Key Settings |
291	|---------|-------------|
292	| `[data]` | CSV paths, date filters (`min_date` = `2006-01-01`, `train_cutoff_date` = `2026-06-01`), `epsilon` for zero-percentage imputation, season ranges, competition codes |
293	| `[features]` | 10 selected match statistics (5 home + 5 away): `GOALS`, `SHOTS`, `SHOTS_ON_TARGET`, `POSSESSION`, `PASS_PCT`; `per_team_count = 5` |
294	| `[training]` | Test split (30%), random state (42), per-classifier hyperparameters |
295	| `[distributions]` | Minimum season (2018), 13 candidate distribution families |
296	| `[simulation]` | Number of simulations (10000), default classifier (`naive_bayes`) — no series length (single-match ties) |
297	| `[visualization]` | DPI (80), matplotlib style (`seaborn-v0_8`), output directory |
298	| `[client]` | Rate-limit delay (6 s, tuned for the free 10 req/min tier), max retries (5), backoff base (2.0), timeout (120 s), custom headers toggle |
299	
300	### `config/playoff_*.toml`
301	
302	Bracket definitions with 16 first-round (Round-of-32) matchups. Each matchup specifies `home`, `away`, and an optional `group` label. **Adjacent matchups feed the next round** — the list order defines the bracket tree (matchup 1 winner meets matchup 2 winner, etc.) — and the matchup count must be a power of two.
303	
304	```toml
305	name = "2026 FIFA World Cup — Knockout (Round of 32)"
306	
307	[[matchups]]
308	home = "Argentina"
309	away = "Saudi Arabia"
310	group = "Top"
311	```
312	
313	## Features
314	
315	Ten feature columns are fed to the classifier — five per team, expressed as football box-score metrics:
316	
317	| Base statistic | Home column | Away column |
318	|----------------|-------------|-------------|
319	| Goals | `GOALS_home` | `GOALS_away` |
320	| Total shots | `SHOTS_home` | `SHOTS_away` |
321	| Shots on target | `SHOTS_ON_TARGET_home` | `SHOTS_ON_TARGET_away` |
322	| Ball possession % | `POSSESSION_home` | `POSSESSION_away` |
323	| Pass accuracy % | `PASS_PCT_home` | `PASS_PCT_away` |
324	
325	Each fitted per-team distribution is over one of the five **base** statistics; the `FeatureSampler` draws one value per base stat for the home team and one per base stat for the away team, concatenating them (home first, away second) into a length-10 vector for `classifier.predict`.
326	
327	## ML Classifiers
328	
329	| Classifier | Key Hyperparameters | Notes |
330	|-----------|-------------------|-------|
331	| **SVM** | `C=0.1`, `gamma=0.1`, `kernel="linear"` | Wrapped in `make_pipeline(StandardScaler(), SVC(..., probability=True))` to prevent data leakage |
332	| **Random Forest** | `n_estimators=500`, `max_depth=50`, `max_features="sqrt"`, `bootstrap=True` | Used directly without scaling |
333	| **Gaussian Naive Bayes** | `var_smoothing=1.87e-07` | Default classifier for simulation; used directly without scaling |
334	
335	Training uses a **temporal split** (`shuffle=False`, `test_size=0.3`) to preserve chronological ordering — later matches form the test set, preventing future-data leakage. The binary target is `1` when the home/favoured team wins.
336	
337	## football-data.org API Client
338	
339	The `FootballClient` wraps all football-data.org v4 REST calls with production-grade reliability:
340	
341	- **Rate limiting** — configurable delay (default 6 s) between calls, tuned for the free-tier 10 req/min limit
342	- **Authentication** — reads `FOOTBALL_DATA_API_KEY` and sends it as `X-Auth-Token`; falls back to unauthenticated access (lower rate) when the variable is absent
343	- **Circuit breaker** — after 3 consecutive failures, pauses 60 seconds and resets the HTTP session before retrying
344	- **Exponential backoff with jitter** — retries on HTTP 429/500/502/503/504 and connection errors, with `wait = backoff_base^attempt + random(0,1)`
345	- **Session recycling** — periodically resets the underlying `requests.Session` (every 50 calls) to prevent stale TCP connections
346	- **Custom headers** — sends a browser-style `User-Agent` and `Accept` headers to avoid WAF blocks
347	
348	### football-data.org v4 endpoints used
349	
350	Base URL: `https://api.football-data.org/v4`
351	
352	| Endpoint | Builder | Purpose |
353	|----------|---------|---------|
354	| `/competitions/{code}/teams` | TeamsBuilder, PlayersBuilder, BracketBuilder | National-team metadata and qualified-team lists |
355	| `/competitions/{code}/matches` | MatchesBuilder | Finished match results per competition-season (`?season=&status=FINISHED`) |
356	| `/competitions/{code}/standings` | RankingBuilder | Group/league standings per season (`?season=`) |
357	| `/teams/{id}` | PlayersBuilder | Squad rosters per team |
358	| `/matches/{id}` | MatchDetailsBuilder | Per-match detail (score; shots/possession/pass on paid tier) |
359	
360	Competition codes queried include the FIFA World Cup (`WC`), UEFA European Championship (`EC`), Copa América (`CA`), and major club leagues for additional historical match volume (`CL`, `PL`, `BL1`, `SA`, `PD`, `FL1`).
361	
362	## Key Design Decisions
363	
364	- **Single-match knockout ties** — the World Cup knockout format has no best-of-N series. `GamePredictor.predict_tie(home, away)` samples one feature vector, runs the classifier once, and returns the winner. `TournamentSimulator._play_tie` resolves each tie with a single prediction; `SimulationConfig` carries no series-length fields.
365	- **Dependency injection** — all components receive their dependencies via constructor; no global state. `GamePredictor` receives classifier + sampler + distributions; the `Pipeline` receives config objects.
366	- **`Classifier` Protocol** — a two-method interface (`fit`, `predict`) in `types.py` that any sklearn-compatible model satisfies, so the simulation layer never depends on a concrete sklearn class.
367	- **Per-team probabilities** — `RoundResult.probabilities` returns each team's advancement probability as `count / n_simulations`. In rounds with multiple concurrent ties, probabilities sum to the number of ties in the round (not 1.0).
368	- **Bracket-tree parity** — `build_bracket_tree()` pairs matchups by adjacent index, exactly mirroring `TournamentSimulator._simulate_once`, so the bracket visualization always matches the simulation topology. The matchup-list length must be a power of two.
369	- **Deterministic stat heuristics** — when the free API tier omits shots/possession/pass-accuracy, `MatchDetailsBuilder` fills them with fixed formulae (never random), so dataset construction is reproducible.
370	- **Checkpointing** — `MatchDetailsBuilder` writes a `.partial` file every 100 matches, enabling resumption after network failures during long downloads.
371	
372	## Results
373	
374	Run 10,000 simulations of the 2026 knockout bracket with Gaussian Naive Bayes and inspect the generated `output/plots/bracket.png` (per-team advancement probabilities and a champion banner) and `output/plots/probabilities.png` (a stacked area chart of advancement probability by team and round). Accuracy depends on the quality and completeness of the downloaded match statistics; the deterministic free-tier heuristics for shots/possession/pass accuracy reduce signal relative to a paid statistics feed.
